metadata.name: Florescence #147
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.

metadata.name: GENERATIVE GLASSES #94
metadata.description:
After 4 months of coding the Generative Glasses is ready! I gained a lot of experience along the way and I really liked the creation process.

I wrote an article in which I report on the creation process in more detail. It can be found at the bottom of the page for related articles.

üëì thousands of different outputs are possible
üë®‚Äçüíª only code
üé® 3D (#webGL #threejs) and 2D (#html5canvas) layers 
üé• animated
üñ±Ô∏è interactive (+controls for mobile)
üòé augmented reality view
üü• different previews: abstract view, product design view, and 2 other view
üñºÔ∏è save images from current view in 4k - 3 different aspect ratio
üìº save animation (from server side) on http://carco.hu

Compositions:

- There is an abstract view where the parts of the glasses are scattered
- There is a front-right view
- Front-left view
- Top view
- Product design view that converts to split screen
- Front view where the object falls apart and starts from the abstract view again

First, one of the 6 compositions comes in and the animation starts. The system randomly determines which composition should be the first in the line. This will also be the saved image that the fxhash system creates. 

If you don't click or touch anything, the animation will loop continuously. If you click into the area anywhere, the controller will appear and the animation will stop. Until you get to the next composition and the animation stops, the pause button flashes until now you can't press anything, all buttons are disabled. If the animation has stopped, the buttons are enabled again, and you can move the camera in 3D space by dragging. 

The controls have left and right arrows that can be used to step between compositions. The animation restarts with the play button.

There are also a few other buttons:

- There is a save button which is a floppy disk. A menu will then appear, offering to save images of different proportions, with the default aspect ratio generated by the program code at the top. (Opening in a new window is required to save an image)

- There is a camera icon that restores the original camera view. It is worth pressing this before saving.

There are options that are not available for all compositions, they only appear if they are enabled in current composition:

- Switch split screen to main camera view, and back (4 squares icon)
- Shows and hide Editing lines (pair of compasses)
- Shows and hide Callout notations (pencil and ruler)
- Shows AR view and stop it (cube icon) (Opening in a new window is required to AR view, more info below)

Keyboard controls:

Press ‚Äú5‚Äù to save image to default aspect ratio
Press ‚Äú6‚Äù to save image to square aspect ratio
Press ‚Äú7‚Äù to save image to portrait aspect ratio
Press ‚Äú8‚Äù to save image to landscape aspect ratio

(Opening in a new window is required to save an image)

Press ‚ÄúArrowDown‚Äù for restores the original camera view
Press ‚ÄúD‚Äù to switch to next composition
Press ‚ÄúA‚Äù to switch  to previous composition
Press ‚ÄúS‚Äù to start animation
Press ‚ÄúSpacebar‚Äù to switch to split screen (if it is available)
Press ‚Äú1‚Äù to hide/show Editing lines (if it is available)
Press ‚Äú2‚Äù to hide/show Callout notations (if it is available)
Press ‚Äú3‚Äù to hide/show AR view (Opening in a new window is required to AR view, more info below)

AR view

If you have a camera on your device, you can try out how such glasses would suit you. This function is not available for all compositions, so if you cannot find the cube icon, tab to the next composition and click on the cube icon. I created this function with the help of Tensorflow face landmark detection package. It's not perfect, there are delays, but it's good enough to try out the glasses.

More information on how were made Generative Glasses in the related article below.

Thank you for your attention! Thanks for the support! Thanks for the opportunity fxhash and genart community! I hope I was able to contribute to generative art with my work!

@C4RC0
carco.hu

metadata.name: In Due Time #72
metadata.description:
‚ÄúIn Due Time‚Äù is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht‚Äôs mastery of line and Vittoria‚Äôs notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria‚Äôs poem for the collection:

‚ÄúIn Due Time‚Äù
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click ‚Äúopen‚Äù under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits ‚Äú1‚Äù through ‚Äú9‚Äù to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Landfill 83 #16
metadata.description:
Landfill 83 is a generative artwork by Estelle Flores in homage to the 40 years of the Christmas release of the videogame "E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial" dubbed 'the worst game of all times'. An event that marked the fate of a nascent entertainment industry, the dumping of thousands of unsold cartridges by Atari in Almagordo landfill in 1983, inspired the artist to create a work reflecting on the industrial exploration of holidays and the destiny of unwanted gifts.

This piece is part of the exhibition Landfill 83 at Entmt., Brussels

(Image composition exploring blending modes on PureSpider template)

metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #117
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographer‚Äôs lenses. Artist‚Äôs role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artist‚Äôs GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

- Use the "A" key to animate (if "Animated" feature is present).
- Press any key to stop the animation.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Balanced #163
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced
